Store bought hummus just won’t cut it after you start making your own - my Creamy Hummus recipe with a herb and garlic topping 🍋 🌿 

Thank you @carolinagelen for inspiring this herb topping - love everything you do girl! 🙏🏼

Hummus Ingredients:
1 can of organic goya or Eden Chickpeas drained and rinsed 
2-3 small garlic cloves 
Juice and zest of 1 small lemon 
3 table spoons HarBracha Tehinni Paste
1/2 table spoon Falafel spice or tea spoon of Cumin spice 
1 tea spoon salt 
Dash of ice cold water or more 
Drizzle Olive oil or more to blend 

Instructions: 
Drain and Place chickpeas in blender and blend. Add garlic, lemon zest and juice, tahini salt and falafel spice and blend. Add ice water and keep blending - this helps break it down and will create a lighter smoother hummus. The less water the thicker it'll be. Add according to preference. 
As it blends, drizzle slowly with little olive oil. Let the blender keep going until you reach a velvety creamy consistency. Around 5 mins. 

For the Herb Garlic oil:
1/3 cup extra-virgin olive oil
3 garlic cloves, minced
1 handful parsley leaves and tender stems, finely chopped
1 handful cilantro leaves, finely chopped 
1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
1 teaspoon hot paprika
1/4 teaspoon cayenne
3/4 teaspoon kosher salt, plus more to taste

Heat the oil in a saucepan for 3 minutes over medium-high heat. In a separate bowl add garlic, parsley, cilantro, pepper, paprika, cayenne, and salt to a bowl. Pour the hot oil in the bowl and let it infuse for 5 minutes.
Swirl the hummus in a shallow bowl, Drizzle some or all of the oil mixture on top. Serve with sliced warm sourdough 

#hummus #hummusrecipe #hummusaddict #recipe #recipeoftheday #vitamix

Our favourite, go to, simple roasted chicken! You see me cooking this every-week, felt like it was finally time to share 😊✨

My simple roasted chicken:
1. Place Sliced onion or shallot at the bottom of a heavy pan, sprinkle with salt 
2. Place chicken legs over the onions. Generously season with salt, pepper, garlic powder, pereg chicken spice. 
3. Add cherry tomatoes and roughly torn parsley. Drizzle the whole pan with olive oil 
4. Add half cup of chicken stock to the bottom of the pan. 
5. Roast 350f for 1-1.5 hours until golden. For a softer pull apart chicken, cover and cook for another 45 minutes.

It consistently blows my mind how many times I use a version of this recipe when cooking. Gremolata is a great way to finish off a dish, it adds that perfect texture and freshness that just lifts everything and makes it better. 
The basic principles for creating Gramalata at home are; a fresh herb, a chopped nut for crunch, citrus zest for that freshness and acidity, maldon salt and then a dash of olive oil for that fat component to combine. Of Course, switching up the type of herb and nut is encouraged, the possibilities, in that case, are endless. Have fun with it. Feel creative. And as long as you have those four foundational ingredients, you can make Gramolata in any of its forms. 

Tip: always use a roasted and salted nut. Unsalted ones just come up bland. 

My go to most versatile combo: chopped pistachios, chopped parsley, lemon zest, Maldon salt and a dash of olive oil. 

My Combination ideas Based on what you are serving it with: 

Sliced rare Meat - chopped tarragon. Little fresh thyme. Mint. parsley. pistachios. Lemon zest. Maldon salt. olive oil 
Roasted Salmon - chopped cashews or peanuts. Cilantro. Scallions. Sesame seeds. Lemon zest. Maldon salt. Olive oil. 
Lamb chops or pulled lamb - chopped mint. Lemon and orange zest. Pistachios or pine nuts. Maldon salt. 
Roasted veges - chopped pistachios. Parsely. Lemon 
Raw fish - chopped basil and cilantro. Lemon orange and lime zest. Chopped jalapeño. Maldon salt. Olive oil. 

#reels #recipe #cleaneating #food

This recipe was inspired by a little restaurant in the middle of the cobblestone streets of Jerusalem. The mismatched chairs, street benches with cats crawling underneath and the strong smells of coffee and cigarettes - that perfect blend of intoxicating Israeli culture i am so drawn to. Although they’re known for their sandwiches, everything on their menu was great. i love everything about Mediterranean cuisine, where food is served simply as is…

This salad is just that, simple and fresh. Uncomplicated. Exactly how I want all my food to be. 🍋

1. Combine all salad ingredients. Combine dressing ingredients, mix well. Dress before serving

It’s all in the truffle 🍷 ✨ 

#truffle  #steak #steakdinner #steakdinner 

Meat by @marble_grain 

RECIPE: 

For the Steak:

3 inch Rib Eye steak 
2 tablespoons olive oil 
Kosher Salt and butchers pepper 
1 sprig Rosemary 
2 cloves or garlic 

Preheat oven to 350F
Bring the steak to room temp. Generously season your steak with salt and pepper 
Heat up olive oil In a cast iron skillet, place steak down and sear on both sides till a nice golden crust develops, aprox 3-4 minutes per side. Add rosemary and garlic half way through and sear along with the steak. 
Place steak on a sheet pan. Set the thermometer to 129F. Insert thermometer inside steak, and Place steak in the oven at 350F
Once the beeper goes off, take steak out and let it rest for 10 minutes 

For the truffle mashed potatoes: 

3 pounds yukon gold potatoes
1 tea spoon kosher salt for seasoning the water
1 tablespoons earth balance room temperature
2 teaspoons truffle zest
1 tablespoon truffle oil
2 teaspoons truffle salt to taste 
Finely Chopped chives to finish (optional) 

Instructions
Cut the potatoes in cubes. Add to a pot of boiling water along with 1 teaspoon of salt.
Boil for 30-45 minutes, until potatoes can be easily pierced with a fork. Drain thoroughly and reserve some water for mashing. 
Place back in the pot and mash (with a potato masher) add in the earth balance, truffle oil, truffle salt. And mash through. If you’re looking for creamier consistency add a dash of reserved starch water and mix to combine. Be careful not to over mash or the potatoes will become gluey.
To finish - add chopped chives and mix to combine. Serve immediately 

 To serve - ladle mashed potatoes in a bowl, place sliced steaks over the mash. Add your roasted tomatoes. drizzle with onion truffle jam and finish with a sprinkle of truffle salt and micro greens.

Roasted Garlic Dipping oil 

3 heads garlic 
1 cup olive oil, plus more for drizzling garlic
Zest of lemon 
4 green olives, minced
2 -3 tablespoon curly parsley, finely chopped 
2 table spoons cilantro 
1/2 red chili, diced (or less if you don’t want it spicy) 
5-6 roasted salted cashews finely chopped 
1 clove crushed garlic 
1/2 table spoon tamari soy sauce 
Sea salt and cracked black pepper 

Preheat an oven 400 degrees F. Slice about 1/8th inch from the top of the garlic bulb. Drizzle with oil, season, wrap in foil, & roast for 40 – 45 minutes, until soft. Squeeze out garlic cloves into a bowl 
Combine your lemon zest and juice, olives, parsley, cilantro chilli, & fresh garlic, and mix into a paste with the roasted garlic. Mound, then place into the centre of a plate. Drizzle around your olive oil, soy sauce, & season the oil with sea salt & fresh cracked black pepper. Done. Serve with warm crusty bread!

Back to school baby 💪🏼✌🏼🚌

Organisation is easy in perfectly curated walk in pantrys, and endless storage kitchens. But what about those small kitchens? The ones with no designated pantry space, small shallows cabinets and pots flying out from everywhere? What people don’t tell you, is that organisation in these kitchens is even more necessary! Ive lived in small kitchens most of my married life and I created my own organised pantries, my little coffee nooks and spice racks all in small closets and spaces. It’s doable. And it genuinely makes cooking so much easier and more enjoyable. 

I’ve taken these containers, racks, storage items to multiple kitchens. Buy once, use multiple times. Thanks @thecontainerstore 

My top 4 tips for how to stay organized in small kitchens: 

1. Minimalist living: regularly declutter. Keep countertops and drawers clear by getting rid of unused items. Keep only essential tools that are used regularly.

2. Smart Storage Solutions: Use labeled containers, racks, turn tables and lucite bins for easy access and to maximize small spaces. 

3. Zone Your Kitchen: Assign specific areas for breakfast, cooking and spices and use smart storage to streamline workflow. Ie turntables for oils and vinegars. 3 - tier shelving for spices and cans 

4. Conscious purchasing: Buy groceries as needed. Don’t overstock. Buy according to storage space and use. 
Ie - don’t buy bulky items that won’t fit. 

My final tip, don’t take it too seriously, this is your kitchen, have fun with it!! 

#kitchenorganization #thehomeedit #organizedhome

4 ingredient chocolate Mousse!! 

I’m not a baker so I always want something super simple and easy to execute! Make in advance and forget about it type dessert… I love that this is only 4 ingredients and still feels so creamy and decadent. pairs perfectly with pomegranates! Happy Almost holidays 🍏 🍯 

4 Ingredient 7th Heaven Chocolate Mousse: 

Ingredients: 
8 oz 7th Heaven hazelnut or classic chocolate 
8 oz non dairy Richers whip for melting chocolate chips
1 cup non dairy Richers whip, for whipping
1/2 teaspoon pure vanilla extract
Pomegranate seeds and sliced figs for garnish 

Instructions: 
1. In a pot, heat 1 cup of cream, add the chocolate and stir occasionally until the chocolate is melted and the mixture is smooth. Set aside to cool to room temperature. 
2. In the bowl with a hand mixer or stand mixer fitted with the whisk attachment, beat 1 cup chilled cream with vanilla extract until stiff peaks form. 
3. Using a rubber/silicone spatula, fold the whipped cream into the melted chocolate. Don’t mix or stir this, gentle folding technique is what keeps this nice and fluffy. Keep folding until fully combined. 
4. Once fully combined, transfer the mousse into a piping bag or zip lock, and dispense into individual serving dishes. chill for at least 2 hours, or overnight in the fridge.  The colder it is, the more firm it will be.
5. Before serving, place pomegranate seeds and sliced fresh figs on top of the mousse, garnish with mint leaves. 

#chocolate #chocolatemousse #dessert #pomegranate

The cauliflower takes Center stage in what is probably one of my favourite sides to serve! central to modern israel cuisine the cauliflower made its debut a few years back. Paired with tahini and some salsa verde, it’ll remind you of some of your favourite Israeli restaurant dishes. 

Whole roasted cauliflower:
1 whole roasted cauliflower 
Olive oil 
Salt 

Bring a pot of salted water to boil. Once boiling add cauliflower, cover and stream for approx 8 minutes until cauliflower can be pierced with a fork but isn’t too tender. Take out and pat dry. 
Drizzle with a generous amount of olive oil and sprinkle with salt. Place in oven at 450/500F and broil until the top of the cauliflower is nice and charred 

Home Made Tehinni:
1/2 cup Har Bracha Tahini 
1/4 Ice water, plus more if needed
1 Lemon zest and juice 
1 garlic clove
½ tea spoon Salt 

Combine all ingredients, minus the ice water, in a food processor or viciBegin blending, as you blend slowly drizzle in the ice water. Blend until fully combined. 
note: you want a thinner consistency tahini for this recipe so you can drizzle it over. Add ice water accordingly. 

Salsa verde: 
One bunch parsley stems discarded 
One bunch mint stems discarded 
One bunch cilantro stems discarded 
2 cloves Garlic 
½ small Red onion 
1/2 cup Olive oil or more if preferred 
Sea salt 

Combine all ingredients in a food processor 
Slowly pulse blender until combined. You should have a blended consistency, but not a paste. 

To Assemble - spoon tahini onto a shallow round dish, place cauliflower ontop and Drizzle with more tahini all over and then with salsa verde. Finish with micro greens

Some Rosh Hashana thoughts ✨

Here we are on the precipice of a new year. 

As we begin to prepare ourselves, I look back at the experiences that defined and also carried us into this moment of newness. I think of the things that tested, and forced us to find the new and more truthful versions of ourselves. 
it is hard to find meaning in our struggle, but also so remarkably magical when the truths become the catalyst for our best growth. And how miraculous when we can turn around and find the light and sweetness through it all. 

A new year of growth is just beyond the horizon, emerging from the void, and filled with endless offerings. 

I’m so Grateful to be part of this beautiful tribe. The one that celebrates life; new beginnings, healing and forgiveness. Together, we find purpose and meaning in our shared journeys. 

Wishing you all a Shana tova - a beautiful, blessed and healthy new year!

Olive oil holds a significant role here - Fat and flavour are foundations that help bring dishes together in ways that make everything come alive. when serving with raw fish, make sure to choose an extra virgin olive oil with robust body and flavour that will add depth and flavour to your dish. 

Salmon crudo Recipe:
Cure salmon:
Sprinkle sushi grade Scottish salmon with generous amount of equal parts salt and sugar. Place in the fridge for 1-2 hours. Take out, rinse and pat dry. 

For the ginger chive dressing:
1 tablespoon chopped scallions 1 tablespoon toasted sesame oil  1 tablespoon fresh lime juice Zest of ½ lime 1 tablespoon mirin dash of soy sauce   1 teaspoon minced Thai red chilli  1 teaspoon grated fresh ginger  dash of honey  1 clove garlic, minced  Salt, to taste Black pepper, to taste

Combine all ingredients. 

To serve: 
Slice salmon into thin pieces. 
Place in bowl and top with chive dressing, thinly sliced shallots, roughly torn cilantro and sliced chili peppers if you like the heat. Finish with a drizzle of good quality olive oil, a sprinkle of Maldon salt and little lime zest.

RECIPE: 

Ingredients:
1 pkg fettuccine pasta (or any other pasta)

1 pkg Cremini mushrooms, sliced
1 shallot, minced
2 garlic cloves, crushed 
3 tablespoons butter
1 tablespoon flour
2 cups whole milk 
1 cup grated Parmesan cheese 
Kosher salt and black pepper to taste 

Instructions:

Cook the pasta according to the package instructions for al dente.
While the pasta is cooking melt 1 tablespoon of butter in a pan, add the shallot, sauté for 1 min.
Add the garlic and sauté for another min then add the sliced mushrooms and sauté for another 3-4 min on medium heat.
Remove from pan and add the remaining 2 tablespoons of butter, once melted and begin to bubble sprinkle in the flour and stir until golden brown, about 1 min.
Slowly pour in the milk while stirring, bring to a simmer then add the grated cheese while stirring. Add the sautéed mushrooms mix together. 
Add 1 teaspoon of salt and taste, adjust and add black pepper according to your preference.
Stir in the cooked pasta.
Plate and sprinkle chopped parsleyc chives or chili flakes (optional).
